<div id="review_2947003076" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2947003076" />
    <a title="Bookworm" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/31167656-bookworm"><img alt="Bookworm" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1508209904p2/31167656.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2947003076?book_show_action=true">Sep 07, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bookworm" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bookworm" href="/user/show/31167656-bookworm">Bookworm</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2947003076" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13282336025850812251">Looking for a book that will spark debate and discussion? This is it! Wow! After reading this book, it is obvious that hospitals need to prepare for disasters and have protocols in place for managing patient care when disaster hits! <br/><br/>This was an articulate and eye-opening account of Memorial Hospital in New Orleans, when hurricane Katrina left the hospital without any power and evacuation opportunities were sporadic at best. Amid the chaos, confusion and disorganization, health professionals did </span>
  <span id="freeText13282336025850812251" style="display:none">Looking for a book that will spark debate and discussion? This is it! Wow! After reading this book, it is obvious that hospitals need to prepare for disasters and have protocols in place for managing patient care when disaster hits! <br /><br />This was an articulate and eye-opening account of Memorial Hospital in New Orleans, when hurricane Katrina left the hospital without any power and evacuation opportunities were sporadic at best. Amid the chaos, confusion and disorganization, health professionals did what they could to help patients evacuate and stay alive. It brings up the ethics of end-of-life care and the fine line between a patient's best interest versus playing God. Very well written and a fascinating look at how important it is to have a strong ethical framework in place to help protect both professionals and patients.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13282336025850812251" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


