    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_671685118" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/671685118" />
    <a title="Rebecca" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5875398-rebecca"><img alt="Rebecca" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1599578317p2/5875398.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/671685118?book_show_action=true">Jul 19, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rebecca" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rebecca" href="/user/show/5875398-rebecca">Rebecca</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9780307718983" href="/book/show/17704494-five-days-at-memorial">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5875398-rebecca?shelf=true-crime">true-crime</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5875398-rebecca?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5875398-rebecca?shelf=reviewed-third-way">reviewed-third-way</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer671685118" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14030187683874349425">The sheer scope of this book is both its triumph and its downfall. Fink has, without a doubt, given the definitive account of the Memorial crisis. In her quest for balanced reporting, she scrutinizes every plot thread, every minor player, every tiny moment that may have led to the climactic decisions made over those five days. Yet this means the resulting chronicle is unwieldy: packed full of details, and swarming with an enormous cast of characters (it takes six pages just to list them all). It</span>
  <span id="freeText14030187683874349425" style="display:none">The sheer scope of this book is both its triumph and its downfall. Fink has, without a doubt, given the definitive account of the Memorial crisis. In her quest for balanced reporting, she scrutinizes every plot thread, every minor player, every tiny moment that may have led to the climactic decisions made over those five days. Yet this means the resulting chronicle is unwieldy: packed full of details, and swarming with an enormous cast of characters (it takes six pages just to list them all). It is a challenge to the reader to keep all the facts in mind while following a narrative arc.<br /><br />For the most part, Fink maintains impressive neutrality. However, at times she paints Dr. Pou as something of a pantomime villain, stalking the hospital halls with a bouffant hairdo and a syringe, poised to strike. (It is almost as if Fink was disappointed by a verdict of innocence...)<br /><br />As far as readable, eye-opening accounts of Hurricane Katrina go, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/189281351" rel="nofollow noopener">Dave Eggers’s Zeitoun</a>, with its compact storyline, is the better book. However, as a study of the deeply divisive ethical issues at work in the Memorial case, as well as an exposé of the woeful unpreparedness of local and national disaster relief agencies, Fink’s magnum opus is worth tackling.<br /><br />(My full review will appear in the July/August 2014 issue of <i>Third Way</i> magazine.)</span>
  <a data-text-id="14030187683874349425" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


